\f2\b Courses of Action
\f1\b0 : The specific "decisions" and "resolutions" made when faced with ethical "gray zones" or situational conflicts.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Influencing
\f1\b0 : The act of "shaping" or "interceding" in the mental process to shift a person toward a specific choice.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Personal Motivation
\f1\b0 : The internal drive that determines what "rewards or outcomes are sought" by an individual, such as seeking free time over money.\cb1 \
\cb3 Two Clear Environmental Value Sets (Environment Act 1986)\cb1 \
\cb3 Under the Environment Act 1986, managers must balance two distinct frameworks:\cb1 \
\cb3 1. 
\f2\b Set One: Intrinsic Ecosystem Values
\f1\b0  These refer to the "inherent worth" of nature that exists independently of human evaluation or utility. They represent an "objectivist" view where value is a property of the ecosystem itself.\cb1 \
\cb3 2. 
\f2\b Set Two: Placed (Assigned) Quality Values
\f1\b0  These are "all values which are placed by individuals and groups" on environmental quality. This represents a "subjectivist" or "anthropogenic" set, where value arises from human interest, preferences, or cultural heritage.\cb1 \
\cb3 Held vs. Assigned Values in Defining Reality\cb1 \
\cb3 Whether values determine reality depends on their classification:\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Held Values (Objective Standards)
\f1\b0 : These are the internal standards or "value-as-criterion" that provide the "invisible architecture" for how a society organizes itself. They act as "psychological properties of the mind" that define what is desirable.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Assigned Values (Object Value)
\f1\b0 : These are the results of an evaluative process where worth is "attributed to an object". In economics, these define reality through "quantifiable metrics" like market price or "willingness-to-pay".\cb1 \
\cb3 Rejection of the "Form of the Good" as a Spiritual End-State\cb1 \
\cb3 The rejection of Plato\'92s 
\f2\b "Form of the Good"
\f1\b0  as the ultimate perfection of human existence can be examined through several critical lenses found in the sources:\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Definitional Simplicity
\f1\b0 : G.E. Moore argues that "good" is a "simple notion" that cannot be defined or broken down, making the search for a "Form" of it an exercise in futility.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Epistemological Blinding
\f1\b0 : Plato himself admitted the Good is "too dazzling" for the naked mind to contemplate, which critics argue makes it an impractical standard for human life.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Subjectivist Critique
\f1\b0 : Subjectivists argue that value is a "relation to an appreciating mind" rather than a sovereign entity in an "intelligible world".\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Akrasia (Weakness of Will)
\f1\b0 : Aristotelian logic suggests a "gap between ethical judgment and behavior," implying that a perfect "end-state" is irrelevant if human emotions and appetites prevent rational adherence to it.\cb1 \
\cb3 Utilitarianism: Value or Derivative?\cb1 \
\cb3 The utilitarian framework\'97the promotion of the "greatest good for the greatest number"\'97is a 
\f2\b derivative
\f1\b0  of teleological normative theory. It is derived from:\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Consequentialism
\f1\b0 : The value of an action is not inherent but is a derivative of its "outcomes" or the "consequent state of affairs".\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Sum-Ranking
\f1\b0 : It derives a "social value" by simply adding up the "surpluses" or "utilities" of individual members, treating the collective value as a mathematical derivative of individual preferences.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Utility Analysis
\f1\b0 : In this view, "value in exchange" is a derivative of "marginal utility," focusing on the quality of outcomes rather than any intrinsic "Form of the Good".\cb1 \
\cb3 Highlight Statement Thoughts for Research\cb1 \
