\cb3 The Efficacy of Concrete Language in Execution\cb1 \
\cb3 Concrete words refer to tangible qualities or characteristics perceivable through the senses, such as 
\f2\b "102 degrees"
\f1\b0  or 
\f2\b "those lime green Nikes"
\f1\b0 , whereas abstract words refer to intangible concepts like 
\f2\b "truth"
\f1\b0  or 
\f2\b "innovation"
\f1\b0 . In the context of business strategy, concrete language is highly effective for the following:\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Increasing Understanding and Memory:
\f1\b0  Concrete language makes complex ideas easier to comprehend and more memorable. For instance, telling a student they must 
\f2\b "work hard"
\f1\b0  is abstract and vague, while providing a list of specific tasks\'97such as 
\f2\b "go to every class"
\f1\b0  and 
\f2\b "write several drafts"
\f1\b0 \'97is concrete and actionable.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Driving Action and Satisfaction:
\f1\b0  In customer service environments, using concrete language has been shown to increase customer satisfaction and even boost subsequent purchase behaviour by 
\f2\b 30 percent
\f1\b0 .\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Focusing on the "How":
\f1\b0  Concrete language focuses on 
\f2\b feasibility
\f1\b0 . If a strategy needs to address the mechanics of an initiative, asking 
\f2\b "how"
\f1\b0  it will be done naturally generates concrete descriptions that are easier for a workforce to follow.\cb1 \
\cb3 The Strategic Power of Abstract Language\cb1 \
\cb3 Conversely, complex business strategies often require 
\f2\b abstract language
\f1\b0  to be effective, particularly during the 
\f2\b visionary or investment phases
\f1\b0 :\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Tapping Into Potential:
\f1\b0  Describing a company's growth potential is often more effective when using abstract language because it focuses on the 
\f2\b "big picture"
\f1\b0  rather than a narrow niche. For example, describing Uber as a 
\f2\b "transportation solution"
\f1\b0  (abstract) rather than a 
\f2\b "ride-hailing app"
\f1\b0  (concrete) makes the potential market seem much larger to investors.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Conveying Purpose and Desirability:
\f1\b0  If the goal is to position a leader as a forward-thinking visionary, abstract language is more effective. This level of language focuses on the 
\f2\b "why"
\f1\b0 \'97the desirability of an initiative\'97rather than just the mechanics.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Providing a Decision-Making Lens:
\f1\b0  Strategic "guiding principles" or 
\f2\b held values
\f1\b0  (like "integrity" or "sustainability") are inherently abstract but provide the 
\f2\b inner compass
\f1\b0  necessary for consistent decision-making in "gray zones" where concrete rules may not yet exist.\cb1 \
\cb3 The "Ascent to the Concrete" in Strategy\cb1 \
\cb3 From a philosophical perspective found in the sources, a truly effective strategy involves an 
\f2\b "ascent from the abstract to the concrete"
