\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 Utilitarian outcomes
\f1\b0  and 
\f2\b intrinsic axiological values
\f1\b0  differ primarily in their foundational criteria for "goodness": utilitarianism is 
\f2\b teleological
\f1\b0 , evaluating actions based on the 
\f2\b desirability of their consequences
\f1\b0 , while intrinsic axiology is 
\f2\b non-instrumental
\f1\b0 , evaluating entities or actions based on their 
\f2\b inherent worth
\f1\b0 .\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb3 1. Teleological vs. Axiological Foundations\cb1 \
\cb3 The fundamental difference lies in the 
\f2\b source of value
\f1\b0 . 
\f2\b Utilitarianism
\f1\b0 , the most prominent teleological theory, holds that a "good" action is one that produces the 
\f2\b greatest good for the greatest number
\f1\b0 . In this framework, the value of an action is a 
\f2\b derivative of its outcomes
\f1\b0  or the "consequent state of affairs". Conversely, 
\f2\b axiological normative theories
\f1\b0  evaluate actions or entities based on 
\f2\b inherent goodness
\f1\b0 , regardless of the outcome. Intrinsic value is defined as being 
\f2\b "valuable as an end"
\f1\b0  or "good in itself," independent of any external factors, utility, or causal chains.\cb1 \
\cb3 2. Instrumental Chains vs. Final Ends\cb1 \
\cb3 The sources distinguish between these two concepts using the 
\f2\b ladder of utility
\f1\b0 :\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Utilitarian Outcomes (Instrumental Value):
\f1\b0  These serve as a 
\f2\b means to an end
\f1\b0 . For instance, money is valued instrumentally because it leads to the purchase of goods, which in turn leads to the experience of pleasure. In utilitarianism, the outcome (pleasure or utility) is the only thing with positive intrinsic value, making everything else a 
\f2\b derivative instrument
\f1\b0 .\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Intrinsic Axiological Values (Final Value):
\f1\b0  These stand at the 
\f2\b endpoint of the chain
\f1\b0 . A thing has intrinsic value if its worth belongs to its 
\f2\b essential nature or constitution
\f1\b0 . G.E. Moore\'92s "isolation test" suggests that if a thing remains valuable even when imagined in total isolation from its consequences, its value is intrinsic.\cb1 \
\cb3 3. Subjectivist Aggregation vs. Objectivist Properties\cb1 \
\cb3 The two concepts diverge significantly in how they are 
\f2\b measured and validated
\f1\b0 :\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Sum-Ranking and Welfarism:
\f1\b0  Utilitarian outcomes rely on 
\f2\b sum-ranking
\f1\b0 , where the total social value is the mathematical sum of individual "surpluses" or utilities. This is often 
\f2\b subjectivist
\f1\b0 , as it depends on an "appreciating mind" or the preferences of a valuing subject.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Objective Intrinsic Nature:
\f1\b0  Many axiological theories (such as those by Plato or Moore) are 
\f2\b objectivist
\f1\b0 , arguing that value is an 
\f2\b inherent property of an object
\f1\b0  that exists independently of whether it is desired, enjoyed, or even perceived by a human evaluator.\cb1 \
\cb3 4. Practical Application: The Environmental Context\cb1 \
\cb3 The difference is most visible in 
\f2\b natural resource management
\f1\b0 :\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Utilitarian Approach:
\f1\b0  Environmental legislation may view nature as a set of 
\f2\b "ecosystem services"
\f1\b0  providing instrumental benefits to humans, such as commercial timber or clean water. Here, the outcome\'97human welfare\'97defines the value.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'95 
\f2\b Axiological Approach:
\f1\b0  Environmental philosophers argue for the 
\f2\b intrinsic value of ecosystems
\f1\b0 , suggesting they have worth 
\f2\b "for their own sake"
\f1\b0 . Under this view, an endangered species or a primary forest possesses a "biotic right" to exist that transcends its utility or the "outcomes" of its preservation for human society.\cb1 \
